e many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Napparius was born in 1198, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1198–Deceased":"1198–Surnud","1223–Female":"1223–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1223":"1223","1198":"1198","Pushull, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1198–Deceased":"1198–Kuollut","1223–Female":"1223–Kuollut","1198–Male":"1198–Kuollut","1223":"1223","1198":"1198","Pushull, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1198–Deceased":"1198–Décédé","1223–Female":"1223–Décédée","1198–Male":"1198–Décédé","1223":"1223","1198":"1198","Pushull, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Napparius est né en 1198, à Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1198–Deceased":"1198–Verstorben","1223–Female":"1223–Verstorben","1198–Male":"1198–Verstorben","1223":"1223","1198":"1198","Pushull, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Robert Napparius wurde 1198 in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochte